  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and expectations for anti-money laundering efforts\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Share evidence and legal resources across jurisdictions\n- Extradition agreements facilitate cross-border legal action\n\n3. Regulatory Frameworks\n- Harmonized reporting requirements\n- Standardized due diligence procedures\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting protocols\n\n4. Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- National agencies exchange information\n- Coordinate international investigations\n- Track and analyze suspicious financial activities\n\n5. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international standards\n- Mandatory reporting of cross-border transactions\n- Risk assessment and monitoring protocols\n\n6. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International economic sanctions\n- Asset freezing mechanisms\n- Coordinated legal actions against money laundering networks\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered approach to combating financial crimes globally.",
